# Pica — Caddy reverse proxy
#
# Caddy is a single static binary (Windows .exe / Linux / macOS) with
# automatic HTTPS. Download it from https://caddyserver.com/download, then
# point it at Pica's loopback listener. Full walkthrough: docs/deployment.md.
#
# Pica listens on 127.0.0.1:8080 by default (config.json host/port). Keep it
# on loopback — only Caddy should reach node.

# ── Public domain (automatic Let's Encrypt certificate) ──
# Replace pica.example.com with your domain. Its DNS A/AAAA record must point
# at this host, and ports 80 + 443 must be reachable for the ACME challenge.
pica.example.com {
	reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:8080
	# Caddy sets X-Forwarded-Proto / X-Forwarded-For / Host correctly and
	# strips client-supplied X-Forwarded-* by default — exactly what Pica's
	# Secure-cookie and HSTS logic expect.
}

# ── LAN / no public domain (local internal CA) ──
# Use this block INSTEAD of the one above when there is no public domain
# (e.g. a Windows 11 machine on the office network). Caddy issues a cert from
# its own local CA. You MUST install Caddy's root certificate on every client
# device (see docs/deployment.md) so browsers trust it — otherwise the
# punch-page geolocation and the Secure session cookie will not work.
#
# pica.lan {
# 	tls internal
# 	reverse_proxy 127.0.0.1:8080
# }
